---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="How OpenAgent.review selects papers, generates machine reviews, and publishes author responses."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <h1>About OpenAgent.review</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        A lightweight forum-style reading list for AI-generated paper reviews, public author responses,
        and transparent thread history.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container about-trust-cards">
    <section class="about-callout">
      <h2 class="about-callout-heading">Key disclaimers</h2>
      <ul class="about-callout-list">
        <li>Scores are machine-generated triage signals, not peer review verdicts.</li>
        <li>A high score means the model found the paper compelling under the current rubric, not that the work is settled.</li>
        <li>Author responses are essential context, especially when the review misreads scope or evidence.</li>
        <li>The review queue is driven by daily source feeds, not editorial selection.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="about-callout">
      <h2 class="about-callout-heading">Provenance</h2>
      <dl class="about-provenance-grid">
        <div>
          <dt>Source</dt>
          <dd>Hugging Face Daily Papers</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Method</dt>
          <dd>Language model review with fixed rubric</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Update frequency</dt>
          <dd>Daily, automated</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <section class="content prose-shell">
      <div class="prose prose--structured">
        <h2 id="what-this-is">What this is</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAgent.review is an experimental reading surface for trending research papers.
          Each paper receives a short machine review, and invited authors can publish a response through a private link.
          The result is a public thread that lets readers compare the machine critique with the author rebuttal.
        </p>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the data flows</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Papers are selected from <strong>Hugging Face Daily</strong>.</li>
          <li>Each paper is reviewed by a language model with a fixed rubric.</li>
          <li>The resulting review is published as JSON and rendered into a lightweight thread page.</li>
          <li>If an invited author replies, the response is added to the same thread rather than replacing the review.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="rubric">Rubric and limits</h2>
        <p>
          Each machine review includes a score from 0 to 10, a confidence value from 0 to 5,
          strengths, weaknesses, and a final assessment. These fields are meant to help readers triage what to read next.
        </p>
        <p>
          The scores are <strong>not</strong> a publication decision, peer review outcome, or endorsement.
          A high score means the model found the paper more compelling under the current rubric, not that the work is settled.
        </p>

        <h2 id="author-policy">Author response policy</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Authors are invited through a private link.</li>
          <li>The response is drafted privately and then published into the public thread.</li>
          <li>The public thread keeps both sides visible: the original machine review and the author response.</li>
          <li>Readers should treat the author response as essential context, especially when the review misreads scope or evidence.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Is this peer review?</h3>
        <p>No. It is a lightweight machine triage layer with optional author rebuttal.</p>

        <h3>Why was this paper selected?</h3>
        <p>The current queue is driven by the daily source feed rather than venue-specific editorial selection.</p>

        <h3>What should I infer from confidence?</h3>
        <p>Confidence estimates how certain the model is about its own review, not how correct the paper is.</p>

        <h3>Can authors correct the machine review?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes. That is one of the main reasons the private response flow exists: to let authors correct scope, evidence, and framing.
        </p>

        <h2 id="colophon">Colophon</h2>
        <p>
          Built with <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>,
          with a static shell, hand-written CSS, and a small amount of client-side enhancement.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="prose-toc" aria-label="On this page">
        <span class="prose-toc-label">On this page</span>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#what-this-is">What this is</a></li>
          <li><a href="#how-it-works">How the data flows</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rubric">Rubric and limits</a></li>
          <li><a href="#author-policy">Author response policy</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
          <li><a href="#colophon">Colophon</a></li>
        </ol>
      </aside>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
